<br>
Notice how some laws are more important than others, such as changing lanes in an intersection versus providing opposition countries with state secrets.  <br>
<br>
Now again, look back at this: I will not fight because I find no point in going in and leveling some country full of people already suffering and who in all likelihood (even if they are Taliban) did not help carry out the attack.  Fine, go in, kill Osama Bin Laden, track down all his associates, kill them as well, jail the people that willingly supported him.  <br>
<br>
The fact that I've made this decision though makes me a criminal in the minds of many, and a coward in the minds as probably more.  It's quite ironic to me that in this time of utter emotional reactions I would be criminalized for having an opposing view and for willing to carry that view to its logical conclusion.  <br>
<br>
We are free until we are told otherwise, and everyone here is telling me otherwise.  Should I have left the country?  Hell no.  I'm just as American as any other guy, I just don't feel like being an American is synonymous with wanting to level 3rd world countries or fighting to police the world against some nebulous &quot;evil&quot; organization.  <br>
<br>
The fact that I'm not American in your way, in the way that you consider &quot;legal&quot; and that the statutes consider &quot;legal&quot; is an entirely relative situation.  We are identified not by the rules we break, but by the values we uphold, and I garauntee I stand by the same values of every American, I just cannot uphold them the way it seems the masses of vengeance wish to. <br>
