I still think of you as a coward.  What is at issue here is not a matter of you conviction that human life is a sacred thing, not to be taken under any circumstances; because if so, you would have to believe that any and all wars are wrong.  That would mean that, for example, World War II was wrong.  So, what you would be saying is that even if the moral cause is correct, we (as a nation) should not go to war. Problem with that is, by not going to war, we are allowing horrible attrocities to be commited.  (The political leaders knew this, if the common citizens didn't)<br>
<br>
You could say, well, we should go to war only if the moral ground for fighting is greater than the sanctity of human life.  In other words, our action should be that which is for the greatest good of humanity as a whole.<br>
<br>
I argue then, that this war with Afganistan is for the greatest good for humanity as a whole.  By apprehending the terrorists responsible, we are providing justice; by declaring war on the governments who harbour these terrorists, we say that we will not tolerate needless destruction of lives, regardless of citizenship. (remember the victims are from many different countries, not just our own)  We are upholding our own idea of right.  Our right, our ideal, that all people are entitled to a life without fear of becoming part of someone else's &quot;political statement&quot;<br>
<br>
You would argue, or so it would seem from yer posts, that we shouldn't reciprocate by killing innocent Afganistanis.  I agree, in principle.  But, I am also a realist.  I know that some innocents may die.  It is the job of our military to make sure innocent people don't get hurt.  The target of any military operations that I am willing to support should only be the Taliban government, and its army, or course.  (and getting the terrorists too, but I am thinking more in a long term, sustained sort of engagement)<br>
<br>
Basically, what I am saying is, our military actions against the Taliban are a defense of freedom.  If America does not respond with military action against this governmental organization, then we are surrendering part of that freedom.  You are saying that you want to be free, but you don't want to pay for that freedom.  It is the job of free men and women to defend their freedom, when need be.  You can thank those that did believe in the defense of freedom for your right to openly state your opinions and beliefs.  Of course, the best way to do that is to honor their memory and example; to do your duty.<br>
<br>
I know that there is nothing I, or anyone short of God, can say to change your mind.  But I want you to know that I think you are a coward.  You are a coward because you refuse to do your duty. I hold my freedom as a sacred right, and will defend it if needed.  <br>
<br>
Kircane <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/umaeri.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Maeri</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 293<br> <font color=#E9D756>(9/27/01 10:17:33 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://users.bigpond.net.au/nettle/eq/maeri/maeri.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The sad situation we find ourselves in...</span><hr size=1> Just adding something:<br>
