[quote]Only if they have some sort of glandular condition. Most human beings at that age [18] are done growing for the most part, physically. You're wrong, consult a text.[/quote]<br>
<br>
Actually, biological adolescence ends around age 24.  I learned this in high school and read a study on it in college.  The biorythms observed in people in their teenage years are the same as people in their early 20s.  You cannot tell the difference in most cases.  Obviously, it stops earlier for some and later for others, but most 24-year-olds' biorythms are indistinguishable from most 15-year-olds'.  <br>
Anyway, what does physical growth mean?  My sister is 5' tall, my brother is 6'4", but I wouldn't say he's more mature than she is!  As for being done growing, don't count on it.  When I went to college at 18, I was 5'3".  I've now in my 20's, and closing on 5'5".  *shrug*<br>
