<br>
Speaking as someone who was "indulged," being indulged does not keep one from growing up.  I had very stern, loving, protective parents, who wanted to shield me from harm -- commendable, no?  That didn't prevent me from growing up.  Now, I have been living on my own since age 21.  I have a long-term, stable relationship with the man I am going to marry.  I have a developing career.  And I have many friends and various interests to occupy my free time.  I think I'm distressingly grown up!  I don't think indulgence has to do with the refusal to grow up, I think that has to do with the individual.<br>
I'd just like to quickly clarify my views.  I support military action.  I do not think people who do not support it should be forced to participate in it.  I oppose the law that requires young men to register for the draft.  I do not support draft-dodging, as it is unlawful; the law is the law, whether I like it or not.  I will never be drafted, but I oppose the draft's existence anyway.  I would make a terrible soldier, in combat or out of it; I don't deal well with authority.<br>
